Visualizing Text and Distributions

Data Visualization Project 03

In this exercise you will explore methods to visualize text data and practice how to recreate charts that show the distributions of a continuous variable.

Part 1: Density Plots

Using the dataset obtained from FSU’s Florida Climate Center, for a station at Tampa International Airport (TPA) from 2016 to 2017, attempt to recreate the charts shown below

library(ggridges)
library(tidyverse)
library(ggplot2)
library(lubridate)
weather_tpa <- read_csv("https://github.com/reisanar/datasets/raw/master/tpa_weather_16_17.csv")
# random sample 
sample_n(weather_tpa, 4)

  1. Recreate the plot below:

library(ggridges)
library(ggplot2)
library(viridis)
## Loading required package: viridisLite
library(tidyverse)
library(forcats)
library(viridisLite)
library(lubridate)

tpa_clean <- weather_tpa %>%
  unite("doy", year, month, day, sep = "-") %>%
  mutate(doy = ymd(doy), 
         max_temp = as.double(max_temp), 
         min_temp = as.double(min_temp), 
         precipitation = as.double(precipitation))
ggplot(data = weather_tpa)+
  geom_histogram(aes(x= max_temp,fill = as.factor(month)),binwidth = 3, color = "white")+
  theme_bw()+
  scale_fill_viridis(discrete = TRUE)+
  facet_wrap(~fct_reorder(month.name[month], month)) +
  theme(legend.position = "none") +
  labs(x = "Maximum Temperatures", y = "Number of Days")

Hint: the option binwidth = 3 was used with the geom_histogram() function.

  1. Recreate the plot below:

plot_2<-ggplot(data = weather_tpa) +
  geom_density(aes(max_temp),bw = .5, kernel = "epanechnikov",
               color = "#2f2f2f", fill = "#7f7f7f",
               size = 1) +
  theme_minimal() +labs(x = "Maximum Temperature")
plot_2

Hint: check the kernel parameter of the geom_density() function, and use bw = 0.5.

  1. Recreate the chart below:

plot_3<-ggplot(data = weather_tpa, aes(x = max_temp, fill = as.factor(month), alpha = 0.2)) +
  geom_density(size = 1) + theme_bw() + scale_fill_viridis_d() +
  facet_wrap(~fct_reorder(month.name[month], month)) +
  theme(legend.position = "none") +
  labs(x = "Maximum Temperatures", y = " ", title = "Density plots for each month in 2016")
plot_3

Hint: default options for geom_density() were used.

  1. Recreate the chart below:

plot_4<-ggplot(weather_tpa, aes(x = max_temp, y = fct_reorder(month.name[month], month), fill = as.factor(month))) +
  geom_density_ridges(bandwidth= 1.49, quantile_lines = TRUE, quantiles = 2, size = 1) +
  theme_bw() + scale_fill_viridis_d() +
  theme(legend.position = "none", panel.border = element_blank()) +
  labs(x = "Maximum Temperature", y = "")
plot_4

Hint: default options for geom_density() were used.

  1. Recreate the plot below:

plot_5<-ggplot(weather_tpa, aes(x = max_temp, y = fct_reorder(month.name[month], month), fill = as.factor(month))) +
  geom_density_ridges(bandwidth= 1.49, quantile_lines = TRUE, quantiles = 2, size = 1) +
  theme_bw() + scale_fill_viridis_d() +
  theme(legend.position = "none", panel.border = element_blank()) +
  labs(x = "Maximum Temperature", y = "")
plot_5

Hint: use theggridges package, and the geom_density_ridges() function paying close attention to the quantile_lines and quantiles parameters.

  1. Recreate the chart below:

options(warn = -1)
plot_6<-ggplot(weather_tpa, aes(x = max_temp, y = fct_reorder(month.name[month], month), fill = stat(x))) +
  geom_density_ridges_gradient(bandwidth= 1.49, quantile_lines = TRUE, quantiles = 2, size = 1) +
  theme_bw() + scale_fill_viridis_c(option = "plasma") +
  theme(panel.border = element_blank()) +
  labs(x = "Maximum Temperature (in Fahrenheit degrees)", y = "", fill = "")
plot_6

Hint: this uses the plasma option (color scale) for the viridis palette.

Part 2: Visualizing Text Data

Review the set of slides (and additional resources linked in it) for visualizing text data: https://www.reisanar.com/slides/text-viz#1

Choose any dataset with text data, and create at least one visualization with it. For example, you can create a frequency count of most used bigrams, a sentiment analysis of the text data, a network visualization of terms commonly used together, and/or a visualization of a topic modeling approach to the problem of identifying words/documents associated to different topics in the text data you decide to use.

Make sure to include a copy of the dataset in the data/ folder, and reference your sources if different from the ones listed below:

  • Billboard Top 100 Lyrics
library(tidytext)
bill_100 <- read_csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/reisanar/datasets/master/BB_top100_2015.csv")

board_100 <- bill_100%>%
  filter(Rank %in% 1:10) %>%
  unnest_tokens(word, Lyrics, token = "words") %>%
  filter(!word %in% stop_words$word, str_detect(word, "[a-z]"))

word_viz <- board_100 %>%
  group_by(word) %>%
  summarise(uses=n()) %>%
  arrange(desc(uses)) %>%
  slice(1:10) %>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_bar(aes(x=word, y=uses, fill= word),
           stat = "identity") +
  coord_flip() +
  theme_minimal()

bill_100 <- read_csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/reisanar/datasets/master/BB_top100_2015.csv")
## Rows: 100 Columns: 6
## ── Column specification ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
## Delimiter: ","
## chr (3): Song, Artist, Lyrics
## dbl (3): Rank, Year, Source
## 
## ℹ Use `spec()` to retrieve the full column specification for this data.
## ℹ Specify the column types or set `show_col_types = FALSE` to quiet this message.
top_5 <- bill_100 %>% mutate(
  Song = factor(Song, levels = c("uptown funk", 
                                 "thinking out loud", 
                                 "see you again",
                                  "sugar", 
                                 "trap queen",
                                 "featuring"
                                 )))
head(top_5, 6) # sample with text column per chapter
## # A tibble: 6 × 6
##    Rank Song              Artist                              Year Lyrics Source
##   <dbl> <fct>             <chr>                              <dbl> <chr>   <dbl>
## 1     1 uptown funk       mark ronson featuring bruno mars    2015 this …      1
## 2     2 thinking out loud ed sheeran                          2015 when …      1
## 3     3 see you again     wiz khalifa featuring charlie puth  2015 its b…      1
## 4     4 trap queen        fetty wap                           2015 im li…      1
## 5     5 sugar             maroon 5                            2015 im hu…      1
## 6     6 <NA>              walk the moon                       2015 oh do…      1
hp_tokens <- top_5 %>% 
  unnest_tokens(word, Artist) %>%
  anti_join(stop_words, by = "word") %>% # remove stopwords
  group_by(Song) %>% 
  count(word, sort = TRUE) %>% 
  top_n(9, n) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  mutate(word = fct_inorder(word))
# create a bar plot showing the token frequency
ggplot(hp_tokens, aes(x = n, y = fct_rev(word), fill = Song)) +
  geom_col() +
  guides(fill = FALSE) +
  labs(x = NULL, y = NULL) +
  scale_fill_viridis_d() +
  facet_wrap(vars(Song), scales = "free_y") +
  theme_minimal()
